SIMPLE: snipe
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Snipe
<hw>Snipe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>snipe</ets>;
akin to D. <ets>snep</ets>, <ets>snip</ets>, LG. <ets>sneppe</ets>,
<ets>snippe</ets>, G. <ets>schnepfe</ets>, Icel. <ets>sn⟦imac⟧pa</ets>
(in comp.), Dan. <ets>sneppe</ets>, Sw. <ets>sn⟦aum⟧ppa</ets> a
sanpiper, and possibly to E. <ets>snap</ets>. See <er>Snap</er>,
<er>Snaffle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of
numerous species of limicoline game birds of the family
<fam>Scolopacidae</fam>, having a long, slender, nearly straight
beak.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The common, or whole, snipe (<spn>Gallinago
c⟦oe⟧lestis</spn>) and the great, or double, snipe (<spn>Gallinago
major</spn>), are the most important European species. The Wilson's
snipe (<spn>Gallinago delicata</spn>) (sometimes erroneously called
<stype>English snipe</stype>) and the gray snipe, or dowitcher
(<spn>Macrohamphus griseus</spn>), are well-known American
species.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A fool; a blockhead.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Half snipe</b></col>, <cd>the dunlin; the jacksnipe.</cd>
-- <col><b>Jack snipe</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Jacksnipe</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Quail snipe</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Quail</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Robin snipe</b></col>, <cd>the knot.</cd> -- <col><b>Sea
snipe</b></col>. <cd>See in the Vocabulary.</cd> -- <col><b>Shore
snipe</b></col>, <cd>any sandpiper.</cd> -- <col><b>Snipe
hawk</b></col>, <cd>the marsh harrier.</cd> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> --
<col><b>Stone snipe</b></col>, <cd>the tattler.</cd> -- <col><b>Summer
snipe</b></col>, <cd>the dunlin; the green and the common European
sandpipers.</cd> -- <col><b>Winter snipe</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Rock
snipe</cref>, under <er>Rock</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Woodcock
snipe</b></col>, <cd>the great snipe.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snipe</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Snipe
<hw>Snipe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Sniped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sniping</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To shoot
or hunt snipe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To shoot at detached men of an enemy's forces at
long range, esp. when not in action; -- often with
<ptcl>at</ptcl>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>snipe at</b></col>, <cd>to aim petty or snide criticisms
at (a person) in his absence.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snipe</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Snipe
<hw>Snipe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To shoot
at (detached men of an enemy's force) at long range, esp. when not in
action.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To nose (a log) to make it drag or slip easily in
skidding.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snipebill</ent>⟦br⟧
